This call can violate Rule 21.17 if sizeof(OS_impl_timebase_table) does not equal the actual number of bytes in the object pointed to by OS_impl_timebase_table. For example, if OS_impl_timebase_table is declared as a pointer (e.g. OS_impl_timebase_record_t *OS_impl_timebase_table) or as an extern/incomplete type, sizeof(OS_impl_timebase_table) yields the size of the pointer (4 or 8 bytes) rather than the buffer size; if the real allocated object size is different (in particular smaller) this memset will access beyond the object bounds. The call is safe only when OS_impl_timebase_table is an array whose sizeof yields the full object size (e.g. a static array sized by OS_MAX_TIMEBASES).
